' Sequence Diagram 09 — Tracker race condition and the locking fix.
'
' Demonstrates the Rust-introduced regression at multi_parent_casper_impl.rs:1046-1075
' where two threads concurrently process AdmissibleEquivocation for the same
' (validator, seqNum-1) pair.  The lock-free direct method calls allow both
' threads to observe "record absent" and both insert, overwriting accumulated
' equivocationDetectedBlockHashes.  Bug fix #2 (T-9.2)
' re-locks the read-modify-write window via access_equivocations_tracker.
'
' Source of truth for Figure 10.2 in slashing-specification.md.
'
' Color palette: see Diagram 02 header for the legend.
'
' Render:
'   plantuml -tsvg docs/theory/slashing/diagrams/09-seq-tracker-race-and-fix.puml

@startuml 09-seq-tracker-race-and-fix
!theme plain

title Tracker race & locking fix (Bug #2 / T-9.2)

skinparam sequence {
  ArrowColor              #444444
  LifeLineBorderColor     #666666
  ParticipantBorderColor  #333333
  NoteBorderColor         #666666
  NoteBackgroundColor     #FFF8E1
  DividerBackgroundColor  #ECEFF1
}
skinparam defaultFontName "sans-serif"
skinparam defaultFontSize 11

autonumber

participant "Thread T1\nhandle_invalid_block(b1)" as T1 #FFECB3
participant "Thread T2\nhandle_invalid_block(b2)" as T2 #FFECB3
participant "EquivocationTrackerStore" as Tk #C8E6C9
database    "KV store\n((Validator, SeqNum) →\n Set[BlockHash])" as KV #C8E6C9

note over T1, KV #ECEFF1
  **Preconditions**
  • Validator A signed b1 and b2 — both at sequence number sn — by the
    same sender, with b1.hash ≠ b2.hash (an equivocation).
  • Both b1 and b2 propagate to the local node concurrently and trigger
    two `handle_invalid_block(...)` invocations on different worker threads.
  • Both threads independently observe "AdmissibleEquivocation" and
    eventually reach the neglect-detection path
    `update_equivocation_records_after_neglect_check(...)` where each
    accumulates evidence at key (A, sn − 1).
  • The KV store starts with NO record at (A, sn − 1).

  **Color legend**
  red = adversarial / regression  ·  orange = detection verdict / slash effect
  green = honest write / Valid    ·  blue = read query
  purple = Rholang invocation     ·  teal = block gossip   ·  gray = internal
end note

== Pre-fix Phase a — handle_invalid_block: both threads insert ∅ ==

note over T1, T2 #ECEFF1
  Both threads enter handle_invalid_block on the
  AdmissibleEquivocation verdict and idempotently
  insert an empty record at (A, sn − 1). This
  step is NOT the source of the race — both
  threads write the same value. The race begins
  in Phase b.
end note
T1 -[#2E7D32]> Tk : insert_equivocation_record(A, sn−1, ∅)
Tk -[#2E7D32]> KV : put((A, sn−1), ∅)
T2 -[#2E7D32]> Tk : insert_equivocation_record(A, sn−1, ∅)
Tk -[#2E7D32]> KV : put((A, sn−1), ∅)\n(idempotent — same value)

== Pre-fix Phase b — update_equivocation_record: lossy RMW (Rust regression) ==

T1 -[#1565C0]> Tk : equivocation_records()
Tk -[#1565C0]> KV : toMap → records_view_T1\n(record at (A, sn−1) = ∅)
Tk -[#1565C0]-> T1 : records_view_T1

T2 -[#1565C0]> Tk : equivocation_records()
Tk -[#1565C0]> KV : toMap → records_view_T2\n(record at (A, sn−1) STILL = ∅ —\nT1 has not yet written its update)
Tk -[#1565C0]-> T2 : records_view_T2
note over T1, T2 #FFCDD2
  Both threads have computed
  newSet := records_view[(A, sn−1)] ∪ {b_i.hash}
  from the SAME pre-image (∅), so each will write
  back a single-element set. Lock-free: there is
  no synchronization preventing the interleaved
  put-after-put below.
end note

T1 -[#2E7D32]> Tk : update_equivocation_record(A, sn−1,\n  newSet = {b1.hash})
Tk -[#2E7D32]> KV : put((A, sn−1), {b1.hash})

T2 -[#C62828]> Tk : update_equivocation_record(A, sn−1,\n  newSet = {b2.hash})
note right of Tk #FFCDD2
  ⚠ T2's write was computed from the stale view
  (∅) it read in Phase b, so newSet = {b2.hash}
  — NOT {b1.hash, b2.hash}. The put overwrites
  T1's write, losing b1's evidence.
end note
Tk -[#C62828]> KV : put((A, sn−1), {b2.hash})\n← final state holds only b2.hash

|||
== Post-fix (T-9.2): access_equivocations_tracker holds the lock ==
|||

note over T1, KV #FFF8E1
  Post-fix represents the proposed patch from
  T-9.2 (see formal/rocq/slashing/theories/T_9_2.v
  for the atomicity proof). It is **not yet
  committed** to the Rust codebase — the live tree
  still uses the lock-free path shown above.
end note

T1 -[#6A1B9A]> Tk ++ : access_equivocations_tracker { f }\nacquires global semaphore
note right of T1
  The closure f runs as one atomic step.
  Read-modify-write is serialized.
end note
Tk -[#1565C0]> KV : toMap → records_view_T1 (∅)
Tk -[#2E7D32]> KV : put((A, sn−1), {b1.hash})\n(update_equivocation_record under lock)
Tk -[#2E7D32]-> T1 -- : ok\nlock RELEASED

note over T2 #FFF8E1
  T2 was waiting for the lock during
  T1's critical section. Now T2 acquires it.
end note

T2 -[#6A1B9A]> Tk ++ : access_equivocations_tracker { f' }\nacquires global semaphore
Tk -[#1565C0]> KV : toMap → records_view_T2\n(record (A, sn−1) NOW present\nwith {b1.hash})
Tk -[#2E7D32]> KV : update_equivocation_record\n  newSet = {b1.hash} ∪ {b2.hash}\n  put((A, sn−1), {b1.hash, b2.hash})
Tk -[#2E7D32]-> T2 -- : ok\nlock RELEASED

note over T1, KV #C8E6C9
  Result of fix: monotone accumulation of
  equivocationDetectedBlockHashes is preserved.
  The post-fix final-state set is the UNION of
  every thread's contribution, regardless of
  scheduling. Proven in Rocq as
  t_9_2_atomic_no_overwrite (single step) and
  t_9_2_atomic_n_threads_arbitrary (n-thread).
end note

@enduml
